#### UUID Generation Using `esp_random`
The most relevant approach for generating a UUID in an ESP32 environment is to use the `esp_random()` function, which provides a cryptographically secure random number generator. A standard way of generating a UUID (version 4) involves creating random bytes and formatting them into the UUID string format (`xxxxxxxx-xxxx-4xxx-yxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx`), where the 13th character is `4`, and the 17th character is one of `8`, `9`, `a`, or `b`.

Here’s a reusable C++ implementation pattern:

```cpp
std::string Board::GenerateUuid()
{
    uint8_t uuid_bytes[16];
    for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) {
        uuid_bytes[i] = esp_random() % 256;
    }

    // Set the UUID version to 4 (random)
    uuid_bytes[6] = (uuid_bytes[6] & 0x0f) | 0x40;
    // Set the UUID variant to DCE (lsb of 7th byte is 1)
    uuid_bytes[8] = (uuid_bytes[8] & 0x3f) | 0x80;

    char uuid_str[37];
    snprintf(uuid_str, sizeof(uuid_str),
             "%02x%02x%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x-%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x%02x",
             uuid_bytes[0], uuid_bytes[1], uuid_bytes[2], uuid_bytes[3],
             uuid_bytes[4], uuid_bytes[5], uuid_bytes[6], uuid_bytes[7],
             uuid_bytes[8], uuid_bytes[9], uuid_bytes[10], uuid_bytes[11],
             uuid_bytes[12], uuid_bytes[13], uuid_bytes[14], uuid_bytes[15]);

    return std::string(uuid_str);
}
```

This snippet:
- Uses `esp_random()` to generate random bytes.
- Sets correct version and variant bits for UUIDv4 compliance.
- Formats the output as a standard UUID string.

This pattern ensures uniqueness and compatibility with systems expecting standard UUID formats.

